WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.240
Okay, ladies and gentlemen, last speaker this morning, Debra, you know what, I have to stop

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:13.240
drinking decaf.

00:00:13.240 --> 00:00:15.960
I'm going to hand you the microphone.

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:16.959
No problem.

00:00:16.959 --> 00:00:24.000
Okay, I am so excited today to talk to you about teacups, giraffes, and R Markdown.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.120
My name is Desiree De Leon, and today I'm going to be talking to you about a project

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:33.439
that I worked on with my co-author, Hassa Wallam, last year to make teaching and learning

00:00:33.439 --> 00:00:38.880
statistics a little bit more inviting, fun, and intuitive, and this was all done using

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:40.919
only an R Markdown website.

00:00:40.919 --> 00:00:45.020
So my goal here today for the next 15 minutes is to kind of give you a quick tour around

00:00:45.020 --> 00:00:50.439
this project and hopefully give you some ideas for what's possible with HTML output of R

00:00:50.439 --> 00:00:55.000
Markdown so that you can incorporate some of these things into your own materials in

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:56.759
the future.

00:00:56.759 --> 00:01:01.840
Okay, so let's start with the problem.

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:06.400
When teaching something that has the potential to be a little bit dry, what is it that makes

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:09.680
it difficult to motivate learners?

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:14.019
Within our own local academic circles, Hassa and I had gotten the impression that many

00:01:14.019 --> 00:01:21.720
people saw statistics as either something unintuitive, scary, or very boring, and we

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:23.800
wanted to see if we could do something about that.

00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:30.360
So we thought, let's teach a really cool stats seminar at our university, and we were pretty

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:37.360
excited about this idea, but for reasons of red tape, our idea for teaching got squashed,

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:43.279
but we decided that we still wanted to make that content and put it online.

00:01:43.279 --> 00:01:48.800
But then that introduces a second problem, which is that we now lose that precious face-to-face

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:55.199
time with students in a classroom that usually adds an additional hurdle for engagement,

00:01:55.199 --> 00:01:59.879
unless we could come up with a way to keep that content compelling.

00:01:59.879 --> 00:02:04.199
And so we thought that we could try this by nesting our statistics lessons inside of a

00:02:04.199 --> 00:02:10.119
story, and we all know that for a good story, you need good characters.

00:02:10.119 --> 00:02:15.160
So really early on in our process, we started to brainstorm some heroes that could play

00:02:15.199 --> 00:02:21.080
the protagonists throughout our statistical content that we were going to be building.

00:02:21.080 --> 00:02:27.639
And ultimately, we came up with the teacup giraffe, which is our fictional little species

00:02:27.639 --> 00:02:30.320
named for its tiny stature.

00:02:30.320 --> 00:02:34.960
And so now we had this hero for all of our stats modules, and we could begin to make

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:39.600
up data about it and build a story around it, and so I just want to give you a small

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:43.240
sampler of what this narrative is like.

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:48.399
So there are two distinct populations of teacup giraffes, each inhabiting their own

00:02:48.399 --> 00:02:50.839
remote islands.

00:02:50.839 --> 00:02:55.759
And as the learner coming to our site, you play the role of the graduate student, and

00:02:55.759 --> 00:03:02.320
you've been tasked with collecting data about this mysterious little species, which the

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:08.039
most sought-after data is about their height, which on both islands is variable.

00:03:08.039 --> 00:03:11.119
Teacup giraffes also really love eating celery.

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:16.880
So by assessing how much of it that they eat, you now have an additional variable to measure.

00:03:16.880 --> 00:03:22.119
And all the while that you're collecting this data, you deal with really demanding emails

00:03:22.119 --> 00:03:27.880
from your advisor back at home, who needs GG plots and other results for these data,

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:30.360
and he needs them now.

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:36.160
But hopefully, teacup giraffes make that a little bit less stressful.

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:41.360
So with this, now you've gotten a little bit of a sampler of the teacup giraffe's world,

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:47.000
and this is actually what served as our backdrop for our equations, our code, and all of our

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:49.839
exercises that we built.

00:03:49.839 --> 00:03:55.479
And actually, we went a little bit overboard in creating this world, because we wrote an

00:03:55.479 --> 00:04:02.559
entire backstory that was completely separate from the stats content, and it's all about

00:04:02.839 --> 00:04:07.880
how the giraffes were discovered, a little bit about their silly behavior.

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:12.119
And at this point, you're probably thinking it's reaching the level of absurdity, and

00:04:12.119 --> 00:04:14.479
I actually agree with you.

00:04:14.479 --> 00:04:18.640
But we hope that all of this storyboarding would really help to suck learners in, and

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:24.799
not only learners, because as content creators, we also got sucked into the teacup giraffe

00:04:24.799 --> 00:04:27.799
world, quite literally.

00:04:27.799 --> 00:04:36.040
Okay, but silliness aside, if you do have some creative muscle that you'd like to flex,

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:39.760
then creating your own good characters is a great way to do that with your educational

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:41.239
content.

00:04:41.239 --> 00:04:45.519
All of the character elements that I've shown you so far here are illustrations that I made

00:04:45.519 --> 00:04:50.880
on an iPad Pro using the Procreate app, but in case drawing your own characters is not

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:55.640
a possibility, there are many other resources where you can find really great high-res and

00:04:55.640 --> 00:05:02.399
open-source images, and one of those is unsplash.com, so I point you there for really strong visuals.

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:08.119
Okay, so usually at this point of introducing the project to someone, most people think

00:05:08.119 --> 00:05:13.320
that we've actually made a children's book and not a stats website.

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:18.619
But our teacup giraffes do have some more utility than just ramping up the delight meter.

00:05:18.619 --> 00:05:24.119
We specifically created our character with our lessons in mind, so in particular, we

00:05:24.119 --> 00:05:29.920
could make things like statistical concepts, like the variance, a little bit less abstract,

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:34.600
because not only do our teacup giraffes provide strong visuals for word problems, like, for

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:39.559
example, asking what percentage of giraffes in our population will be shorter than this

00:05:39.559 --> 00:05:46.600
little guy here, but maybe a more subtle benefit is that we can use our character to link to

00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:48.720
otherwise less intuitive concepts.

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:54.000
For example, by using the spots, the color of the spots on our characters to show and

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.619
illustrate the concept of the sum of squares and how you build that, which is a precursor

00:05:58.619 --> 00:06:02.200
for calculating the variance.

00:06:02.200 --> 00:06:07.279
So with good characters, we now had one pillar in place to help make our content feel a little

00:06:07.279 --> 00:06:09.959
bit more friendly.

00:06:09.959 --> 00:06:13.200
And the next step was to include good play.

00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:17.959
And by that I mean taking full advantage of the HTML output that you get with our markdown

00:06:18.119 --> 00:06:22.679
by inserting movement and interaction so that the learner actually has something that they

00:06:22.679 --> 00:06:24.440
can do on your site.

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:28.519
And I just want to share five examples of packages and tools that we found most useful

00:06:28.519 --> 00:06:30.559
for this.

00:06:30.559 --> 00:06:32.399
The first one is Plotly.

00:06:32.399 --> 00:06:37.480
So Plotly lets you create clickable and interactive plots so that a learner can see a concept

00:06:37.480 --> 00:06:39.519
play out in real time.

00:06:39.519 --> 00:06:44.880
This, for example, is a Plotly plot that we used to explain why the equation for sample

00:06:44.880 --> 00:06:49.399
variance needs to be divided by n minus 1, and we, of course, explained this in the text

00:06:49.399 --> 00:06:52.519
before showing this plot.

00:06:52.519 --> 00:06:57.540
And another good thing that you can use for good play is the Gifsky package, which lets

00:06:57.540 --> 00:06:58.920
you make GIFs.

00:06:58.920 --> 00:07:05.640
And so once you've installed Gifsky, you can include an animation hook in the code chunk

00:07:05.640 --> 00:07:11.160
settings, and this will stitch together any plots that are output from that code chunk.

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:15.980
So this GIF here was made by throwing several ggplots in one code chunk and then looping

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:23.519
through all of them with something like either a per function or an apply function.

00:07:23.519 --> 00:07:27.760
But you can actually use the Gifsky hook to make GIFs out of regular images as well, so

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:30.160
you're not just limited to ggplots.

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:35.200
This is a GIF that we made to represent very abstractly the process of going from cross

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:43.079
products to covariances and then standardizing those to become correlation scores.

00:07:43.079 --> 00:07:47.899
But the most important part of good play that we wanted to give our learners was the ability

00:07:47.899 --> 00:07:52.540
to go through some stats methods by hand, or in other words, we wanted learners to have

00:07:52.540 --> 00:07:57.920
a chance to break apart functions, write their own functions, at least ones to kind of eliminate

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:02.839
that statistical black box feeling, and in order to do that, we needed interactive console

00:08:02.839 --> 00:08:06.119
windows in our site.

00:08:06.119 --> 00:08:13.519
So our solution was to take a LearnR window and embed it into our R Markdown website.

00:08:13.519 --> 00:08:15.119
Here's an example of how this works.

00:08:15.119 --> 00:08:21.200
So if you have not seen the LearnR package before, LearnR documents are R Markdown documents

00:08:21.200 --> 00:08:26.200
that can be used as interactive tutorials, and they usually exist as standalone things

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:30.679
or standalone apps, but what's really cool about them is that they have these built-in

00:08:30.679 --> 00:08:35.679
little consoles, so you can preload code into them for a learner or text.

00:08:35.679 --> 00:08:41.239
You can also preload solutions, which a user can then run and see their output, and that's

00:08:41.239 --> 00:08:47.119
great.

00:08:47.119 --> 00:08:54.840
So one of the problems, however, is that when a user is using a LearnR document in the iframe,

00:08:54.840 --> 00:09:00.200
it's a little tricky to get it to resize appropriately when the user is interacting with it, and

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:05.640
so a solution to get it to resize appropriately is to use a little bit of JavaScript, and

00:09:05.640 --> 00:09:11.599
in particular something called an iframe resizer, which does exactly what it sounds like.

00:09:11.599 --> 00:09:16.280
So to our knowledge, this is the first time that someone's applied an iframe resizer to

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:21.400
a LearnR window that's inside of an iframe, and the process for it is a little bit involved,

00:09:21.400 --> 00:09:25.140
so I'm not going to cover the details here, but I have created a step-by-step guide that

00:09:25.140 --> 00:09:31.900
shows you how to do this in your own R Markdown documents, and you can find that on my blog,

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:37.460
which is at deseret.rbind.io.

00:09:37.460 --> 00:09:41.219
And LearnR windows are not the only things that you can embed, of course.

00:09:41.219 --> 00:09:45.700
There are two more quick pieces of good play that I'd like to share with you that are considerably

00:09:45.700 --> 00:09:47.739
easier to embed in your site.

00:09:47.739 --> 00:09:51.979
So first there's a regular shiny app like this one, which we used to have learners guess

00:09:51.979 --> 00:09:59.020
correlation values, and using the same iframe approach, you can also embed quiz questions,

00:09:59.020 --> 00:10:03.700
and we haven't yet done this in our project, but we look forward to asking really tough

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:06.780
quiz questions like this one.

00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:08.539
Okay.

00:10:08.539 --> 00:10:13.900
So by using Plotly, Gifski, LearnR, and Shiny, we could make our R Markdown site so much

00:10:13.900 --> 00:10:17.739
more interactive, and there's still one more piece missing that I'd like to share, though,

00:10:17.739 --> 00:10:21.340
about our site, and that is good design.

00:10:21.340 --> 00:10:26.140
And so by this I mean the page layout and styling that's distinct from the content,

00:10:26.140 --> 00:10:31.460
but brings good vibes and a sense of polish to your product.

00:10:31.460 --> 00:10:38.179
So essentially judging a book by its cover or by extension, judging a site by its HTML

00:10:38.179 --> 00:10:39.940
and CSS.

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:44.059
And while this is, of course, not the best way to measure the quality of your content,

00:10:44.059 --> 00:10:49.460
the degree of styling that you give your site not only changes a learner's first impression

00:10:49.619 --> 00:10:54.059
when they first see your page, but it can also improve readability, navigation, and

00:10:54.059 --> 00:10:58.700
the user's general experience as they go through your content.

00:10:58.700 --> 00:11:02.539
So out of the box, here is what our R Markdown site might have looked like just using the

00:11:02.539 --> 00:11:05.940
default settings for an R Markdown website.

00:11:05.940 --> 00:11:09.460
And this is a decent start, but I want to share three things that I think deliver some

00:11:09.460 --> 00:11:11.020
pretty big impact.

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:14.539
And the first is decluttering.

00:11:14.539 --> 00:11:20.880
So we do this by getting rid of borders and highlights and numbers that are not absolutely

00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:22.859
essential to our output.

00:11:22.859 --> 00:11:27.239
And then we can add a whole lot more white space so things don't feel so cramped.

00:11:27.239 --> 00:11:31.780
So around the table of contents, between paragraphs and headers.

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:35.340
We can also constrain the width of the body of the text.

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:40.780
And finally, we can increase font size and the line height of the paragraph, too.

00:11:40.780 --> 00:11:45.020
And so once we've made these changes, we get a lot more breathing room on the page

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:47.700
and it's easier to read.

00:11:47.700 --> 00:11:53.299
Most of these changes do involve a little bit of CSS, but if that scares you, one non-CSS

00:11:53.299 --> 00:11:57.820
thing that you can do in your R Markdown document, straight in the document itself, is just by

00:11:57.820 --> 00:12:03.219
adding backslashes or line breaks on their own lines.

00:12:03.219 --> 00:12:09.500
And adding that space in between is manually something that goes a long way when it comes

00:12:09.500 --> 00:12:12.460
to making more breathing room.

00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:16.539
And so here's kind of the before and after just with these, like, right off the bat changes

00:12:16.539 --> 00:12:20.659
of more white space and breathing room.

00:12:20.659 --> 00:12:24.099
The second thing I want to share about good design is setting the visual ambiance for

00:12:24.099 --> 00:12:30.299
the site by adding a big image to the top, which in the lingo is called a hero image.

00:12:30.299 --> 00:12:35.280
And so you can do this if you're familiar with the R Markdown setting for the includes

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:40.000
before body option, and you can just insert a file in there that references some big

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.919
image to go at the very top of your page.

00:12:44.919 --> 00:12:50.000
And finally, making use of built-in features of Pandoc, which is what runs under the hood

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.479
of R Markdown, to make things like note boxes.

00:12:53.479 --> 00:12:58.219
So these can help organize your page content and help call out things like instructions

00:12:58.219 --> 00:13:01.559
or notes or critical thinking questions for your learners.

00:13:01.559 --> 00:13:06.520
Here we've used them to encase the learning objectives for this particular module.

00:13:06.520 --> 00:13:10.960
And the step-by-step process for making these note boxes is also something that you can

00:13:10.960 --> 00:13:15.000
find on my blog.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.400
So there's some other things that you can tweak as well.

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:22.719
Things like adding a logo, Google fonts, you can customize your nav bar.

00:13:22.719 --> 00:13:26.840
And these and many other good design elements I've shown you today are things that, again,

00:13:26.840 --> 00:13:28.840
involve some CSS.

00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:34.719
If your experience with CSS in the past has been either difficult or nonexistent, I hope

00:13:34.719 --> 00:13:37.239
that this does not stop you.

00:13:37.239 --> 00:13:42.239
So this past summer I interned at RStudio with Allison Hill, and we started to create

00:13:42.239 --> 00:13:48.039
some R Markdown templates so that you can create these very same layouts in an out-of-the-box

00:13:48.039 --> 00:13:49.280
way.

00:13:49.280 --> 00:13:55.679
These two are still works in progress, but the resources called RStudio for EDU and RMD

00:13:55.679 --> 00:14:01.599
for EDU will be coming to a GitHub repository near you, so you can keep a lookout for those

00:14:01.599 --> 00:14:04.479
later this year.

00:14:04.479 --> 00:14:08.960
So now I've shown you some examples of good characters, good play, and good design.

00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:13.119
And I think it's worth mentioning that all of these things are things that Hass and I

00:14:13.119 --> 00:14:19.000
did without ever needing to leave the comfort of our favorite IDE.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:23.479
And with that, I can now show you what it looks like when you put all of these things

00:14:23.479 --> 00:14:24.479
together.

00:14:25.359 --> 00:14:29.359
If you'd like to check out the wonderful world of teacups, giraffes, and statistics, you

00:14:29.359 --> 00:14:33.119
can do that at bit.ly.

00:14:33.119 --> 00:14:38.200
For the best experience, I recommend doing that on desktop and in the Chrome browser.

00:14:38.200 --> 00:14:42.440
But the source code for all of this project is something that you can also get to by clicking

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:46.000
on the GitHub logo and the nav bar of the site, and that will take you straight to the

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.320
GitHub for it.

00:14:48.320 --> 00:14:52.479
We're still in development for this project, and we're just starting to test this out with

00:14:52.479 --> 00:14:58.640
real live learners, but we welcome GitHub issues and blog comments or come find us at

00:14:58.640 --> 00:14:59.640
some point.

00:14:59.640 --> 00:15:02.440
We'd love to get your feedback and hear your questions about it.

00:15:02.440 --> 00:15:07.320
I hope this has given you some ideas for what's possible to make when you're teaching with

00:15:07.320 --> 00:15:11.640
our markdown, and we hope that you can incorporate some good characters, good play, and good

00:15:11.640 --> 00:15:14.119
design in your next project.

00:15:14.119 --> 00:15:17.919
And so with that, I'd like to thank my co-author, Hass Olam, for being the other half of this

00:15:17.919 --> 00:15:22.440
project, Allison Hill for helping me package up so many of these designs and layouts in

00:15:22.440 --> 00:15:26.640
a way that I'll be able to share with all of you soon, and also Carl and the rest of

00:15:26.640 --> 00:15:30.280
the education team for their support of the giraffe project.

00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:33.799
And if you want to hear or if you want to find out more about me or see what I'm posting

00:15:33.799 --> 00:15:38.280
on Twitter, you can do that at these different handles, and thank you guys so much for your

00:15:38.280 --> 00:15:39.280
attention.

00:15:39.380 --> 00:15:56.599
So first, that's the first time I've ever had somebody come in exactly on time to the

00:15:56.599 --> 00:15:59.000
second, so well done.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:04.320
First question, for people with no design background, do you have any recommended resources

00:16:04.320 --> 00:16:05.640
or starting points?

00:16:05.640 --> 00:16:06.919
Yeah, certainly.

00:16:06.919 --> 00:16:10.719
So the things that I've been developing with Allison Hill I think will be a great start

00:16:10.719 --> 00:16:15.520
for that, so that our studio for EDU, I mean, again, those things are still in development,

00:16:15.520 --> 00:16:19.919
but I think it's important to note, so when Hass and I started this project, neither of

00:16:19.919 --> 00:16:23.020
us had any knowledge of CSS.

00:16:23.020 --> 00:16:29.000
It mostly started off as, oh, we saw this really cool thing online, let's start Googling,

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.119
is this possible to do with our markdown, and we didn't know the right search terms

00:16:34.119 --> 00:16:35.520
or anything like that.

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:40.919
So I think if you have enough grit and perseverance, you can get anything that you see out there

00:16:40.919 --> 00:16:47.200
on the internet to work with our markdown, but the things I'm working on with Allison

00:16:47.200 --> 00:16:49.280
will hopefully make that process easier.

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:55.280
Okay, and the second one is, how are you going to tell whether this is actually helping people

00:16:55.280 --> 00:16:56.280
with the stats?

00:16:56.280 --> 00:17:03.219
Yeah, that's a great question, so that comes as soon as we start getting feedback from

00:17:03.219 --> 00:17:04.219
real learners.

00:17:04.219 --> 00:17:08.140
So we have Google Analytics up, which are helpful to some degree, but I think we need

00:17:08.140 --> 00:17:12.339
to pilot this out in real classrooms to see what the in-person learner thinks about it,

00:17:12.339 --> 00:17:17.819
and then from there we can think more creatively about how to get feedback from online learners.

00:17:17.819 --> 00:17:21.619
Third question is, have you been thinking about taking this to the general public, the

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:24.219
sort of audience that our previous speaker was talking about?

00:17:24.219 --> 00:17:28.380
Yeah, so I mean, I guess the idea is that we want to reach as many people as possible.

00:17:28.380 --> 00:17:32.020
That was part of the reason why we wanted to make this content feel as friendly and

00:17:32.020 --> 00:17:36.339
fun as we hope that it does.

00:17:36.339 --> 00:17:40.780
I mean, if we can make something appealing to people who have never even previously thought

00:17:40.780 --> 00:17:45.699
they'd be interested in stats, then we think that we can reach a lot of different communities

00:17:45.699 --> 00:17:46.699
and groups of people.

00:17:46.699 --> 00:17:47.699
So, next step.

00:17:47.699 --> 00:17:50.699
Okay, and last question before we break for lunch.

00:17:50.699 --> 00:17:53.380
You said that a lot of people looked at this and thought that you were actually writing

00:17:53.380 --> 00:17:55.160
a children's book instead.

00:17:55.160 --> 00:17:58.380
Have you thought about writing a children's book?

00:17:58.380 --> 00:18:01.939
I would love to write a children's book.

00:18:02.859 --> 00:18:08.780
Well, I've helped with a children's book, one that is co-authored by Greg Wilson.

00:18:08.780 --> 00:18:10.420
I guess, should we announce?

00:18:10.420 --> 00:18:12.619
I don't know if you want me to announce it.

00:18:12.619 --> 00:18:14.180
You should turn this into a children's book.

00:18:14.180 --> 00:18:15.180
Oh, okay.

00:18:15.180 --> 00:18:18.180
Round of applause if you want this turned into a children's book.

00:18:18.180 --> 00:18:22.979
Okay, so there's your second.

00:18:22.979 --> 00:18:26.060
And again, please, one round of applause for all four of our speakers.

